'Parlophone' is a record label that was founded in Germany in 1896 by the Carl
LindstrÃ¶m Company as Parlophon. The British branch was formed in 1923 as
"Parlophone Records" which developed a reputation in the 1920s as a leading jazz
label. In 1926, Columbia Graphophone Company acquired the Parlophone business,
label name and its titles. Columbia Graphophone later became Columbia Records,
and then EMI. The Parlophone label continues to be used. On 21 September 2012,
regulators officially approved Universal Music Group's planned acquisition of
EMI, on condition that Parlophone is divested from the combined group. The entity was called the Parlophone Label Group until it
found a buyer. However, the early Parlophone titles are now in the public
domain. Warner Music Group have acquired Parlophone for Â£487 million. http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/legal-and-
management/1561787/warner-music-groups-acquisition-of-parlophone This made
Parlophone WMG's oldest unit, surpassing Atlantic Records. Warner Music will
make Parlophone WMG's third label group alongside Atlantic and Warner Bros. Records. http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/global/1559599/warner-
music-group-outlines-parlophone-integration-process-expects

George Martin joined EMI in 1950 as assistant label manager, taking over as
manager in 1955. Martin produced and released a mix of product including comedy
recordings of The Goons, the pianist Mrs Mills, and teen idol Adam Faith. In
1962 Martin signed rising new Liverpool band The Beatles. With Cilla Black,
Billy J. Kramer, The Fourmost, and contemporary Mancunian band The Hollies also
signed to the label, Parlophone in the 1960s became one of the world's most
famous and prestigious record labels.

For a long time Parlophone claimed the best selling UK single "She Loves You",
and the best selling UK album [[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band
(album)|Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]. The label also achieved
placement of seven singles at #1 during 1964, when it also claimed top spot in
the album charts for 40 of the 52 weeks during that year.
